1v. 9, 10. In l. 9 all MSS. read Vulture in Apulo, but in l. ιο the

majority have limen Apuliae, though sorne of the best have limina Pulliae. The reading limen Apuliae is impossible, sor the initial vowel of Apulia is long and Apulo has immediately preceded. The reading limina Pulliae is possible if Pullia be supposed to be the nurse’s name. Inscriptions of Samnium and Campania show that the name was pretty common there. (See C. I. L. vols. 9 and ιο.) Editors have tried all- manner of emendations: e. g. sedulae Bentley, villulae Yonge, pergulae Housman. Keller reads avio for Apulo in l. 9.
